The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 NHPC drive to hike capacity

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 More power

 Mumbai, April 6: National Hydroelectric Power Corporation Ltd (NHPC), the largest hydroelectric power generating company in the country, has outlined an expansion programme, under which 12 additional hydroelectric projects will come up in Bengal, Jammu amp; Kashmir, Himachal Pradesh, Arunachal Pradesh, Assam and Sikkim. 

 The projects are expected to increase the companys total installed capacity to over 5,192 mw from 2,755 mw. 

 NHPC is also set to tap the capital markets with an initial public offering (IPO), which comprises a fresh issue of over 111 crore shares and an offer to sell over 55.86 crore shares of the government. After the issue, the governments stake in NHPC will come down to 86.30 per cent. 

 In its draft prospectus filed with the Securities and Exchange Board of India, NHPC has said while its power stations and hydroelectric projects are located predominantly in the north and northeastern parts of the country Jammu amp; Kashmir, Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand, Manipur and Sikkim it is now building 12 additional hydroelectric projects in various states.

 In Bengal, NHPC took control of the Teesta III low-dam hydroelectric project in November 2000. 

 The project is located on the river Teesta in Darjeeling district and is expected to start operations in September 2008. NHPC is planning to spend over Rs 2,500 crore in this fiscal on the project. 

 In addition to these projects, the company is also working on joint ventures with various state governments. It is expected that if the projects are implemented, the installed capacity could go up another 5,030 mw. 




